Thermodynamic optimization of a linear thermomagnetic motor

Lorenzo S. CorrÃªa a, Andrew Rowe b, Paulo V. Trevizoli a,â

a Department of Mechanical Engineering, Federal University of Minas Gerais (UFMG), Belo Horizonte, MG, 31270-901, Brazil

b Institute for Integrated Energy Systems (IESVic), University of Victoria, Victoria, British Columbia V8W2Y2, Canada


A R T I C L E I N F O A B S T R A C T


Keywords:

Energy harvesters Thermomagnetic motor Gadolinium

Entropy generation minimization Back work ratio

Optimization

Thermomagnetic motors can be applied to recover low-grade thermal energy waste and convert it into mechanical energy, therefore, used as an energy harvester. The present work proposes a mathematical model to simulate the heat transfer and the thermodynamic cycle of a linear thermomagnetic motor coupled to a spring mechanism. The simulation results are the input information in a subroutine to optimize the motor design based on two objective functions: to minimize the total entropy generated and to minimize the back work ratio, defined as the ratio between the pumping power and the total produced power. The mathematical model solves coupled the energy equations for the fluid and solid phases, and the entropy generation model includes four contributions: interstitial heat transfer (finite temperature difference), axial conduction in the fluid and solid phases, and viscous dissipation. Gadolinium is used as soft magnetic material due to the availability of properties data. Four design and operating conditions constraints are taken into account: heat exchanger length, spring constant, mass flow rate, and warm stream temperature (heat source), and their optimized values are, respectively, 52 mm, 1560 N/m, 80 kg/h at any warm stream temperature ranging from 310â330 K. At these combinations, the optimum thermomagnetic motor is able to produce a net power of 5.00 Â± 0.15 W with a minimum back-work ratio of about 12%. The proposed methodology can be used to optimize the design of novel thermomagnetic motors or to optimize geometric parameters and operating conditions of state-of-the-art concepts.



  1. Introduction


    Energy conversion processes occur in the presence of several types of losses and irreversibilities. Heat losses are often observed in machinery and systems due to imperfect thermal insulation, whereas heat rejection processes are an intrinsic part of thermodynamic cycles. In the latter, fluid streams transport thermal energy which is disposed to the nearby environment as heat waste. In principle, waste heat at temperatures differing from the environment has the potential to be converted to a useful form of energy, whether mechanical or electrical.

    Forman et al. [1] estimated that 63% of the total thermal wastes are at temperatures below 100â¦ C (low-grade heat waste), mostly found in electricity generation systems. Waste heat with temperatures up to 230â¦ C is the most abundant, however, they are often rejected to the environment because they present low exergy (Carnot efficiency, considering the cold sink at 27â¦ C and the hot source at, maximum, 230â¦ C) [1,2]. In this temperature range, conventional power cycles may not be economically viable, while solid-state energy harvesters can be successfully employed and worth further investigation. Among those, thermomagnetic motors and generators are promising alternative

    systems to recover low-grade heat waste and convert it to mechanical or electrical energy, respectively [3â5].

    Thermomagnetic motors (TMM) rely on the temperature and magnetic field dependence of the properties of soft magnetic materials (MM) around their magnetic transition temperature (ððð or Curie

    Temperature) to produce motion (rotary or linear) and mechanical

    power. The magnetic field gradient defined between the low field and the high field regions establishes the potential to produce motion, and the magnetic force or torque is proportional to the mass/volume of the MM, specific magnetization intensity and the magnetic field gradient [6].

    Thus, thermomagnetic motors are mainly composed of a magnetic field source to produce a high field region and to consolidate the magnetic field gradient; the MM with a transition temperature higher than the ambient; the heat source (at ðð» ) and heat sink (at ðð¶ ) - where

    ðð¶ < ððð < ðð» - and; in some designs, a pumping system. The

    MM is processed as a heat exchanger in a certain geometry (such as microchannels, parallel plates, and packed beds) to enhance the heat transfer with the fluid streams, and thus it is called Magnetic Heat Exchanger (MHex). Considering that the MM is initially cooled down

    field along its gradient and stops at a position where the force balance is respected. At this point, the MM is now heated up by a hot fluid stream (at ðð» ) pumped from the heat source. When its temperature gets higher than ððð , shifting to a non-magnetic phase (low specific magnetization), the MM has little magnetic attraction. Hence, it can be moved out of the high magnetic field region, by the use of gravity, or a spring, or coupled to a second MM in the ferromagnetic phase (attracted by the field), returning to the initial position [4,5,7].

    Some experimental and numerical studies have been reported in recent years, but firstly it is important to cite the work done by Murakami and Nemoto (1972) [8], who developed a rotary prototype. The authors concluded that to increase the efficiency of a TMM it was necessary to have a more intense magnetic field and materials with higher specific magnetization coupled to larger thermal conductivity and lower specific heat capacity. The discovery of novel materials the giant magnetocaloric effect (MCE) [9,10] and the recent developments of permanent magnet magnetic circuits for applications in magnetic refrigeration [11,12], refreshed the perspectives for the development of more efficient TMM.

    With respect to experimental works, different concepts have been tested. A review on TMM prototypes and their performances has been published by Kishore and Priya (2018) [4]. Among those, it is important to discuss the work by Takahashi et al. (2006) [13]. Their design has three magnetic field sources to increase power and, as a result, the maximum measured (cycle average) is in the order of 4 W at a rotation speed of 24 RPM. Following a similar idea, Mehmood et al. (2021) [14] used two magnetic field regions and small blocks of gadolinium (Gd) as magnetic material. They measured a maximum power of â 1 W at a rotation speed of 220 RPM. Another recent work by Kaneko et al. (2021) [15] describes a linear TMM using Gd spheres packed in a porous media and two magnetic field regions with intensities close to

    0.85 T. The authors showed that the use of porous media is able to guarantee a shorter cycle period (2 s, thus 30 RPM rotation speed), but the produced power was low, around 0.44 W. Possibly, the forces, torques, and powers of the latter could be improved by using more intense magnetic fields. It is important to mention that all of those are small-scale prototypes, and none of those were designed based on optimization procedures.

    Regarding simulation works, different approaches have been proposed. Kishore and Priya [2], Bessa et al. [16], and Lima et al. [17], developed a mathematical model to simulate thermodynamic cycles. This approach enables a rapid evaluation of the specific work, first and second law efficiency as a function of the heat source and heat sink temperatures, and low and high field intensities. Such results are important for an initial evaluation of the operating condition, as well as to compare different thermodynamic cycles or employed magnetic (magnetocaloric) materials. But, they are limited and do not provide information regarding cycle periods and net powers, for instance.

    A second type is heat transfer models, in general, with numerical solutions. This approach enables the evaluation of forces, torques, cycle periods, and produced/net power. Alves et al. [18] simulated a rotary TMM using different MM: gadolinium, FeNi alloy, and MnAs

    magnetocaloric material. The latter presented shorter periods and lower forces, while the FeNi alloy presented the opposite. Gabrielyan et al. [19] implemented a 3D heat transfer model in ANSYS to simulate a disc-type TMM. The disc had several plates of gadolinium parallel to each other and water is pumped among them. The authors reported some recommendations for a future design of this concept of TMM. Kishore and Priya [20] implemented a 3D model in COMSOL and evaluated the work and power density of a linear TMM, varying the heat source and sink temperatures. They estimated a work of 0.6 J/kg per cycle and a power density of 0.2 W/kg using gadolinium as MM. Evaristo et al. [21] simulated a linear TMM counterbalanced by the gravitational force. The MHex has a circular channel geometry and the model included internal demagnetization fields, viscous dissipation, and axial conduction losses. The results showed that the proposed geometry is not suitable to achieve low cycle periods, thus, to enhance the produced power it is necessary to use porous geometries (such as a packed bed of spheres) to achieve high heat transfer rates. In contrast, such porous geometries demand high pumping powers.

    Some works also performed a numerical-experimental evaluation. Franzitta et al. [22] used the dq-axis theory of electric machines to model a rotary TMM, and compare its results with experimental data finding a good agreement. Thus, the model showed to be satisfactory and quite simple enabling its use for optimization purposes. The same group later reported in Ref. [23] the optimization results for the same motor, proposing the maximization of the electric torque as objective function.

    In this context, some important remarks can be made: (i) the necessity to develop novel experimental apparatuses to evaluate the potential of TMM; (ii) experimental data are also needed to evaluate losses impacts and to validate numerical models; (iii) the MHex must be designed considering high heat transfer rates geometries to reduce cycle periods and increase the produced power, however, as the expense of higher pressure drops; (iv) lastly, the application of TMM for heat recovery, since heat is already available, the thermodynamic efficiency can be evaluated based on the ratio between the pumping power and the total produced power, this is, the back work ratio used to evaluate Brayton cycle (gas-turbine engines) [24].

    The present work develops a thermodynamic optimization procedure that can be used in the design of optimal TMM or to optimize geometric or operating conditions of state-of-the-art TMM. The approach uses a combined evaluation of two objective functions based on the first and second law of thermodynamics: (1) to minimize the back work ratio and, (2) to minimize the total entropy production along a cycle [25]; both considering a fixed net power (we assume 5 W). The net power is the difference between the total produced power and the pumping power. It is important to mention that this is the first work to consider the use of the back work ratio to evaluate and optimize TMM. A similar strategy was used by Pussoli et al. [26], and Trevizoli and Barbosa [27] to optimize peripheral finned-tube heat exchangers and active magnetic regenerators, respectively, where heat transfer rates or cooling capacities were kept fixed.

    A 1D, transient heat transfer mathematical model is implemented to simulate the thermodynamic cycle of a linear TMM coupled to a spring mechanism, which stores mechanical energy along a specific period of the cycle. This design is assessed due to the feasibility to be later built and tested for the improvement and validation of the model. The mathematical model solves coupled the energy equations for the fluid and solid phases (thermal non-equilibrium in a porous medium). Gadolinium spheres (packed bed) are used as soft magnetic material due to the availability of properties data, while a mixture of water

    optimized parameters for the linear TMM. Four design and operating conditions (independent variables) are considered: MHex (porous medium) length, spring constant value, mass flow rate, and warm stream inlet temperature.

    3. Optimization routine and parameters


      This work proposes the use of two objective functions to be minimized at a fixed net power, to find optimum operating and geometrical parameters to design a proof-of-concept linear TMM. They are:

Considering the dependent and independent variables values/ranges selected in this work, ðÌ ððð¡ values can range from 3 up to 6 W, but results for 5 W will be evaluated and discussed in-depth.

Four parameters are selected as independent variables and can be changed in accordance with a specific range as in Table 2.

      These independent variables are selected because:


      • ðÌ ð : it has a direct impact on the heat transfer and viscous dissipation, as well on the ðµð ð and entropy production values;

      • ð¿ðð»ðð¥: a larger MHex increases the MM mass, thus, the magnetic force, but pressure drops also increase, impacting the ðµð ð and entropy production;

  5. Conclusions


This paper presented an optimization procedure based on the minimization of the back work ratio and the Entropy Generation Minimization (EGM) method to design a proof-of-concept linear thermomagnetic motor coupled to a spring mechanism able to provide a net power of 5 W. Four geometric configurations and operating conditions are taken as independent variables: mass flow rate (ðÌ ð ), heat exchanger length (ð¿ðð»ðð¥), spring constant (ðð ððððð ) and warm stream temperature (heat source, ðð ð¤).

A 1D model was developed to solve the heat transfer in the porous medium coupled to the thermomagnetic phenomena. The model outputs (cycle period, displacements, total produced power, pumping

minimizes ðµð ð, but not the entropy generated. This way, ðµð ð is

a more representative figure of merit to be evaluated and minimized when designing thermomagnetic motors. It is important to mention that, to the best of the authorsâ knowledge, this is the first work to consider ðµð ð to evaluate and optimize TMM for energy harvest applications.

In addition, it was not possible to find an optimum value for ðð ð¤. The ðð ððððð and ð¿ðð»ðð¥ have no sensibility with respect to ðð ð¤, while the mass flow rate is little affected. Thus, the optimized design can operate at any value of ðð ð¤ in a range from 310 K up to 330 K, and still

meet the requirements of producing a net power of 5 W with minimum values of ðµð ð. On the other hand, ðð ððððð values showed to have a major impact on the results, and it was possible to find an optimum

The final proposed optimized configuration and conditions were: ðð ððððð,ððð¡ = 1560 N/m, ð¿ðð»ðð¥,ððð¡ = 52 mm and ðÌ ð ,ððð¡ = 80 kg/h, which is able to produce â to any ðð ð¤ in a range from 310 K up to 330 K â a net power of 5.00 Â± 0.15 W and a
